<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Caillech wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Just curious -- why even put a pause? My macro:
<br />

<br />
/rs TASHED {{{ %T }}}
<br />
/cast #
<br />
/cast #
<br />

<br />
I just don't see the point in making a delay. The cast time on tash is too short to really require one. You can tell the raid a mob is tashed and then immediately cast it. The mob will be tashed before they finish reading your message.
<br />

<br />
Not really a big deal though. /shrug</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I would switch the /rs and the casting. There is an inherent pause in macros after any chat lines, so you delay the casting of the spell by as much as a second, sometimes a tad more. If you swap them, you will begin casting, and the chat will be done before the spell finishes casting. On Tash, it isn't that big a deal since it casts so fast, but if you do it with anything longer, those seconds can be detrimental.
<br />

<br />
I learned this from making healing macros...where every second counts.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
